# Other things

Gaming is important but there are a few other things I configured.

## Web browsing

While I don't think Isidor will (or should) browse the web much yet I think it's prudent to set it up properly before that time comes.

[CachyOS][] installs Firefox as the default browser, which is great.
To kill ads I installed [uBlock origin][] and I also run [Adguard Home][] on my router where I block social media on his computer.

I don't like that my kids freely watch YouTube as there's way too much crap on YouTube to poison their brains.
I've been meaning to migrate everything to [Jellyfin][] where I could download "approved" channels/videos but I haven't gotten there yet.
As a compromise I installed [Unhook][] to get rid of recommendations and shorts from YouTube.

Finally, I replaced Google with a [Kagi Family account][] for search.

::: note
I had to change the DHCPv4 settings for the Wifi to "automatic (only addresses)" (or similar, the OS is in Swedish) and manually add my DNS server to be able to block websites using [Adguard Home][].
:::

## Music

Isidor has been absolutely enthralled by the music from Kpop Demon Hunters and he really wanted to listen to it on his own computer.

Simple solutions are the best so I setup desktop shortcuts to [Music Assistant][] and Spotify via Firefox.

## Coding with Sonic Pi

I went to the [Goatmire Elixir 2025][] conference where Sam Aaron [gave a talk bout teaching programming by creating music](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1pB0_PU520E)
and it was the most inspiring talk from an excellent conference.

I want to introduce programming to my kids one day so I decided to install [Sonic Pi][], the tool Sam created
to do just that.

Unfortunately, I had a bunch of problems getting it installed.

There's a [sonic-pi repository][] on the Arch User Repository.
I used the AUR helper yay to install it and the dependencies:

```fish
sudo pacman -S --needed git base-devel
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/yay.git
cd yay
makepkg -si
```

And then install with:

```fish
yay -S sonic-pi
```

After a while it installs but crashes at `pw-jack not found`.
I fixed that by installing `pipewire-jack` (replacing `jack2`):

```fish
sudo pacman -S pipewire-jack
```

Then I could launch [Sonic Pi][] but I didn't get any sound.
That was solved by launching `pavucontrol`, setting the headphone output as the default, disabling the HDMI output, and rebooting.

Now I get sound but for some reason [it does not recognize the Enter key][], making it impossible to use properly.

_This_ is the vintage Linux experience I have so very vivid memories about...

